Cobalt-60 formation for cancer therapy. Abstract A cobalt-60 source, suitable for cancer therapy, has been developed. The source consists of an alumina matrix containing 2.5 mg of CoCl 2 ·6H 2 O and 0.5 mg of stannous chloride. The matrix is sealed in a stainless-steel capsule and pressurized with helium gas. The source was operated at 10 atm pressure and 80 degrees C. The radiation emitted from the source was measured with a Geiger-Müller counter. The radiation was 90% gamma rays and 10% beta rays.
